export const chapterTranslations39to40: Record<number, string[]> = {
  39: [
    // P0
    "To return to our story: Wang Xun had been unable to keep his appointment at the Yi Garden the other day, for Sun Lianggong had engaged him to help arrange the wedding, and he had spent several days running about on the matter. The ceremony was set for the tenth day of the second month — not many days off. At the New Year, Li Xingquan had sent several hundred taels of silver to Yuanmao, along with a letter to Wang Wenhui asking him to arrange his son's marriage. Wang Wenhui had no patience for matchmaking and delegated everything to Wang Xun. Li Yuanmao then sought out Wei Pingcai and begged him to take charge of all the arrangements. Wei Pingcai had been carousing for over a month — spending, losing at cards, and frittering away a good deal of money — and the theft case had still not been resolved, so his spirits were rather low and he was at a loss for what to do. When Li Yuanmao came to him, Pingcai reflected that he himself had originally served as co-matchmaker with Wang Wenhui, and that this would give him a convenient pretext for visiting Wenhui again. So he agreed, then added, \"That bracelet you borrowed from me last year — it's time you returned it. Every day you delay, the interest mounts.\" Yuanmao said, \"Father only sent three hundred taels, and I'm afraid that's barely enough to cover the wedding. I've nowhere else to borrow, so if you press me on that debt, you'll be the death of me.\" Pingcai said, \"What a strange thing to say — how does asking for what's mine put you to death? What did you tell me last year? That you'd repay me the moment you heard from home. Now I find it hard even to ask.\" Yuanmao said, \"Don't worry. Once I've moved into the house, I'll redeem it for you.\" Pingcai said, \"Once you've moved in, you'll have even less money.\" Yuanmao said, \"I may not have money, but she ought to.\" Pingcai said, \"She? Who?\" Yuanmao laughed. \"My wife, of course. Not just this one debt — I have all sorts of plans that depend on her.\" Pingcai laughed. \"Your wife is going to be a source of funds?\" Yuanmao said, \"What an absurd idea!\" Pingcai said, \"But you just said so yourself — you were going to draw on her.\" Yuanmao said, \"I only mean that she'll have a dowry, and once she's married to me it'll all be mine anyway. Would I really be unable to get a single bracelet back?\" Pingcai said, \"A man who lives off his wife's purse is no man at all.\" Yuanmao said, \"What's the harm? It's not like living off someone's shame.\" The two men joked and laughed for a while, and then Yuanmao left.",

    // P1
    "The following day Pingcai called on Wang Wenhui, but Wenhui had gone into the yamen; Wang Xun received him instead. They then went together to pay their respects to Lianggong, exchanged the usual pleasantries — that they were currently sojourning away from home, that they had no one to look after things, and so on — and begged for his forbearance. Lianggong said, \"We are joining hands because we love the same family; all this formality can be dispensed with. I don't want to cost the other side a single cash. Leave everything to me.\" He then kept Pingcai to dine.",

    // P2
    "Three days before the wedding came the exchange of betrothal gifts, and Pingcai had no choice but to go and find Yuanmao, which meant calling on Madam Yan as well. Having stayed away for several months and having caused that unpleasant scene the previous year, he was quite ill at ease. Madam Yan, for her part, asked nothing about past events and exchanged only a few bland words with him. When Pingcai went to see Ziyu, Ziyu — who still remembered what Qinyan had said some days earlier — bore him a quiet grudge and was noticeably less warm toward him than before.",

    // P3
    "All the arrangements for Yuanmao's affairs were handled by Mei Jin, who procured hairpins and bracelets, embroidered silks and gowns, and borrowed from Madam Yan a pearl crown, jade sash, official rank-badge robes with court beads, embroidered dragon skirt, and other finery, arranging everything in sixteen lacquered boxes and erecting a ceremonial bower — a respectable enough display. The two matchmakers escorted the gifts over. The Sun household accepted them and sent back the return-boxes with gifts of commensurate value, nothing particularly rare or precious.",

    // P4
    "On the auspicious day the household of the Mei family saw to all the preparations, laying on two tables of wine — one for Madam Yan, one for the matchmakers — and inviting Ziyu and Yan Zhongqing to keep them company. Zhongqing said, \"Brother Yuan, tonight you truly arrive at the summit of the Jade Mountain.\" Wang Xun said, \"A life of glory and splendor all the way to white-haired age.\" Ziyu said, \"'Still they say the lamplight shows two shadows face to face — the more you rub your eyes, the blurrier they grow.' That is a poem about a nearsighted man in the bridal chamber; it would do nicely for Brother Yuan this evening.\" Yuanmao said, \"I've always thought nearsightedness had its advantages — even if the bride is a bit plain, you can't see her clearly.\" Zhongqing said, \"But if she should turn out to be beautiful, wouldn't that be a waste?\" Yuanmao laughed. \"I rather doubt my bride will be a beauty. I've heard a few things — I'll just hope she doesn't resemble the two brothers in looks.\" When the auspicious hour arrived, they all escorted Yuanmao to the Sun residence, where he was welcomed with drums and music. The young lady in question was the daughter of Lianggong's first wife; the current Madam Sun did not dote on her especially, and so the whole affair was conducted simply. Among the female guests, only the sister-in-law of Madam Lu — the wife of Lu Zongyuan — had come, bringing her young daughter. The groom's family had offered their congratulations in the morning. It was Ji Lianghuan who was making a show of festivity; he was privately hoping to rowdy up the bridal chamber, and had the two useless brothers to receive him.",

    // P5
    "Yuanmao and his new bride performed the wedding rites before the bridal candles, were escorted to the bridal chamber, sat upon the bed while wedding verses were scattered over the curtains, drank from the crossed cups, and then the groom was called back out to sit at the great banquet table. Sihui and Siyuan kept them company for a while, until Wang Xun and Zhongqing proposed moving the party into the bridal chamber to drink more freely. Everyone filed into the bridal chamber. Zhongqing said, \"Tonight we get to look at the new bride,\" and made as if to approach the bed. By the bed stood two elderly escort-women and two small maidservants. Siyuan, afraid that Zhongqing might lay eyes on his sister, ran to the bed and seized hold of the curtain, managing to push out a few \"look\" sounds and then, with a great effort, the two words \"not permitted,\" which made the whole company burst out laughing. Wang Xun pulled Zhongqing over and made him sit down, but Siyuan still wasn't reassured and kept his grip on the curtain door, so that everyone continued to laugh under their breath. Sihui said, \"The marriage chamber is the foundation of the greatest human bond; how should outsiders intrude? We may count ourselves fortunate that a brother guards the bedside against all insult. Otherwise, that which is white as snow would be viewed by ten pairs of eyes.\" Ziyu heard this and broke into laughter. Wang Xun said to Zhongqing, \"It is as the old text says: 'Arouse not my temper, lest even the dragon bark.'\" Zhongqing smiled faintly. Li Yuanmao drank his wine with an air of supreme self-satisfaction.",

    // P6
    "Ji Lianghuan had met Wang Xun and Zhongqing on several previous occasions, but this was his first meeting with Ziyu, whom he eyed with private admiration: \"This young master Mei is a fine-looking man — compared to that old Sihui of the Sun family, it's like comparing the heroic generals Cen Peng and Ma Wu to some stage ruffian.\" Pingcai asked Ji Lianghuan, \"I haven't seen your master come out in days — what's he doing at home?\" Lianghuan said, \"My master has been indisposed these past couple of days and hasn't been able to get about.\" Pingcai said, \"What sort of indisposition?\" Lianghuan said, \"I hear it's a boil on his leg; that's why he hasn't gone out.\" The table that evening was divided into three separate clusters: Ziyu, Zhongqing, and Wang Xun formed one group; the Sun brothers Sihui and Siyuan another; and Pingcai and Lianghuan yet a third — so the gathering never warmed into real conviviality. Wang Xun, always amiable by nature, saw how the company was failing to mix and made a determined effort to draw everyone together. By this time the seating in the bridal chamber had been taken without any ceremony of deference. Pingcai and Lianghuan sat on one side; Zhongqing and Ziyu on another; Yuanmao sat alone at the head; and Wang Xun sat below with Sihui.",

    // P7
    "Someone called Siyuan to come over, but he would not leave; he pulled up a stool and planted himself in front of the bed-curtain. Ji Lianghuan turned to Ziyu with a grinning smile and said, \"Elder Master Mei rarely goes out in company, and today is the first time I have had the honor of your acquaintance. If you're inclined, why not come visit my master one of these days? He is a most agreeable person.\" Ziyu, not knowing whose household was being spoken of, gave a vague reply, then quietly asked Wang Xun, who answered that it was Xi Shiyi. A sudden surge of indignation filled Ziyu and he said nothing more. Lianghuan then turned to Yuanmao: \"Your future wife, my cousin's cousin on the other side, is a paragon of virtue — Brother Li is truly fortunate to have arranged such a fine match. Our mutual kinsman will be posted to a province before long — either Kuizhou in Sichuan or Chenzhou in Hunan. As the son-in-law of the family, you'll travel together to his posting, and it won't just be as a secretary — I should think the entire household, inside and out, will have to rely on you.\" Zhongqing found this amusing and could not help asking, \"And how exactly are you related to the Sun household?\" Lianghuan said, \"The legitimate sister-in-law of Elder Sun's mother-in-law is the elder cousin on my mother's sister's side, through her legitimate niece on the paternal line — that's the recent connection. Going back to the older tie: the maternal grandfather of the late mistress of the house was the father-in-law of my father-in-law.\" Zhongqing started laughing. Pingcai said, \"That's a connection so light you'd call it eggshell blue.\" Lianghuan said, \"Though slender, it still beats having no kin at all. I've heard a couplet that goes: 'What writings could astonish all within the seas — when not a single friend or kinsman stands at court.'\"",

    // P8
    "He continued, \"But that's a careless thing to say. All of you gentlemen here have the court full of close friends and worthy associates. Take the two members of our host's family — they speak for themselves. Brother Li, the new son-in-law, is the son of the prefect; Elder Master Mei is the son of the School Inspector; Elder Master Wang is the son of the Vice-Minister; and Elder Master Yan is the Vice-Minister's own son-in-law. Even Master Wei was once an honored guest in the household of the Lord Hua — practically a deputy to the young master. You are all men of distinction. Only this humble nobody here is a mere secretary's secretary, and I shall have to beg your generous patronage and assistance in future, your support and kind mention.\" This speech fairly turned everyone's stomach. Zhongqing could not contain himself and said, \"The way Master Ji works out these connections, we all become kinsmen — it merely requires a few more turns in the pedigree.\" Lianghuan agreed heartily. Ziyu smiled. Yuanmao said, \"Not only can I not follow the connections, I couldn't even hear them properly — it's like a pumpkin vine tangled up with a bean vine.\" Pingcai laughed and said, \"And in the middle of it all you run into a man with his legs all wrapped in creepers.\" Sihui said, \"Kin love is the way of kin — whosoever has blood and breath cannot but honor his kin. To love one's kin is humanity; humanity is humanity itself.\" Siyuan, hearing his elder brother open his mouth, immediately set about refuting him. \"Th-th-that s-s-saying,\" he stuttered, \"is n-n-not — right. You s-say whoever has b-b-blood and breath honors their k-k-kin, meaning everyone is your kin. I — I th-think only the c-c-crab has no blood — the turtle still has blood, so I suppose the t-t-turtle is your kinsman too. I haven't g-g-got so many relations myself.\" He burst out in a loud laugh, and the whole room laughed with him. Sihui said, \"What a fool — not worth speaking to.\" Siyuan said, \"I'm not a f-f-fool — you're the one who's d-d-dead. 'The dead man prizes nothing — the humane man prizes his kin.'\" The company laughed all the louder at this.",

    // P9
    "Zhongqing said, \"I have a ready-made joke for the occasion. One day the Dragon King of the Sea was releasing the various monsters to be reborn into the world, and had already freed a great many. At last a night-patrolling Yaksha dug two creatures out of the mud and begged the Dragon King to let them go. The Dragon King looked: one was a soft-shelled turtle, the other a toad. The Dragon King said, 'I'm not entirely easy about letting these two go — have them bring a guarantor.' The turtle, hearing this, pointed to the Minister Tortoise standing nearby and said, 'He is my kinsman,' and then pointed to General Snake and said, 'And he is my relation.' The Dragon King said, 'If the Minister is your kinsman, that's quite sufficient — why bring in a General as a relation as well?' The turtle replied, 'Not only a relation, but something of a kinsman too. We turtles cannot father our own young; we must invite a snake to do it for us. Though the lineage is tortoise, the seed is serpent — so the snake counts as both a relation and a kinsman.' The Dragon King laughed and said, 'Since you have such distinguished kinsmen and well-connected relations, I'll let you go.' He then called the toad forward and asked, 'And do you have kinsmen and relations?' The toad said, 'Every man is my kinsman; every person is my relation.' The Dragon King said angrily, 'How can that possibly be?' The toad said, 'Our kind is born from the spare essence that men leave in the privy — so we resemble men in our form. If that doesn't make every man my kinsman and every person my relation, what does?' The Dragon King cried out in alarm: 'Release him at once! Otherwise he'll start claiming kin with me, and I don't want a toad for a cousin.'\" At this, Pingcai, Wang Xun, and Ziyu nearly fell off their seats laughing. Sihui and Lianghuan, knowing themselves to be the butt of the joke and having no reply, had to swallow their indignation. Siyuan, however, seeing those two mocked, laughed all the louder. \"A f-f-fine turtle kinsman!\" he cried. \"A f-f-fine toad r-r-relation!\" Wang Xun said, \"I have a joke of my own. There was a blind prostitute, and when men came to her she couldn't see them, but she could somehow tell them apart by rank. One day she received three clients, and her procuress afterward asked her: 'Miss, can you guess what manner of men your three visitors today were?' The blind girl said, 'The first was a scholar, the second was a criminal-law secretary, and the third was a nearsighted simpleton.' The procuress said, 'How could you tell them apart?' The blind girl said, 'The first came up very properly and carefully separated my two — parts — then brought them together again, made me face one way and then the other, and I heard him murmur: softer here, firmer there; one deep, one shallow — he was composing an eight-legged essay. So I knew he was a scholar. The second came in, poked about for a while, then examined me closely. I heard him say: a scar on the left temple, a fingernail mark on the right breast, an inch and two-tenths long at a slant. Presently he said: both legs stretched straight, both arms spread wide. Wasn't that the style of a coroner examining a body-in-evidence? So I knew he was a criminal-law secretary. The third was the strangest of all. The moment he came in he peered at my — private parts, and his eyebrows were like a brush, and they tickled me dreadfully. He peered, then sniffed; sniffed, then peered again. From that I knew he was a nearsighted simpleton.'\" The whole company burst into laughter — even the old escort-women and the little maids laughed. And from behind the bed-curtain came a barely perceptible tremor of suppressed merriment: the bride herself was laughing, covering her mouth tightly. Siyuan said, \"Th-th-that n-nearsighted one sounds just like Brother Li, and that c-c-coroner one is just like B-Brother Ji.\" Lianghuan laughed and said, \"Not at all, not at all. I am quite certain it wasn't the coroner — it must have been the one who examines the body after the inquest.\" Li Yuanmao said, \"I don't believe eyebrows can actually tickle.\" Ziyu laughed. \"Your own eyebrows are by no means light.\" Sihui said, \"Of the three, I am studying the one who composes eight-legged essays.\" Pingcai said, \"I have a joke too. Two brothers, both nearsighted, yet neither would admit it. The elder always said the younger's eyes were bad; the younger always laughed at the elder's poor sight. Next door there was a local-deity shrine that had just hung a new plaque. The two brothers agreed to go test their eyes — to see which of them could read the plaque most clearly. The two of them were unfortunately both quite short. The elder first made the younger crouch down, then climbed onto his shoulders and had him stand up, so they could get close to the plaque. The elder squinted carefully at it, then came down and said to the younger: 'Let me lift you up to look.' The younger went up in the same fashion, looked, and immediately asked his brother: 'What characters did you read?'",

    // P10
    "The elder said, 'I read it as a pawnshop sign — so there must be a pawnshop inside. I clearly made out the characters tu ye dang — meaning even earth can be pawned. Let's go home and carry over a couple of loads of earth to pawn.' The younger laughed: 'Brother, you've misread it. I read it as shang ta dang — meaning you've been taken in. If we haul over the earth and they won't accept it, haven't we been made fools of?' The elder thought his brother had a point, so they both went home. Another day the two brothers decided to have another contest of eyesight. The younger said, 'Brother, you shouldn't compete with me. Say you describe my appearance and I describe yours — but since we can't see ourselves, we wouldn't believe each other. Now, my sister-in-law's face I can clearly recall, and you must know your younger sister-in-law's face well enough. Let's each describe our wife's appearance and see whose eyes prove sharper.' The elder thought this was sound reasoning and nodded, but when he tried to recall his wife's face it was a blur and he couldn't bring it to mind. The younger thought it over at length and couldn't picture her either; so each hurried off indoors. The elder went home and couldn't find his wife anywhere; after some searching he found her in the mill-room, just sifting flour, her whole face powdered white as snow. He leaned in close and peered at her face very carefully, then walked out and sat down to wait for his brother. The younger ran to his own room, found the door shut, pushed it open. His wife had just taken off her trousers to step into the basin for a bath; seeing her husband enter, she was embarrassed and grabbed the nearest thing to cover her lower parts. There was a fly-whisk within reach, so she held it up over herself. The younger, seeing those trailing silky threads, was quite astonished, and stooped down to examine them closely before going out.",

    // P11
    "He found his elder brother sitting there grinning, and asked, 'What's so funny?' The elder said, 'Brother, I confess my eyes are worse than yours. I've been married five years and only today have I seen her clearly. Who would have thought — your sister-in-law is an albino: a whole head of white hair.' The younger also sighed and said, 'Brother, sister-in-law's white hair is nothing remarkable. I just now got a good look at your younger sister-in-law, and all her — intimate hair — is white as well.'\" The company let out a roar of laughter. Then suddenly from behind the curtain the bride's voice rang out in fury: \"Who is that shameless wretch over there talking his filth! Your mother's an albino! Your grandmother's an albino!\" Before she had finished, something flew out from behind the curtain and smashed two dishes of food. Everyone was so startled they looked at one another in mute bewilderment. Siyuan, seeing his sister had started cursing, leapt to his feet and joined in. The party broke up at once in embarrassment; everyone scrambled to their feet and hurried out, going their separate ways as fast as they could. Yuanmao and Sihui were left with no way to rein things in and could only see the departing guests to their carriages before going back inside.",

    // P12
    "As it happened, Pingcai's joke — though he had aimed it at Li Yuanmao's nearsightedness — had unwittingly landed on a tender nerve where the bride was concerned. As had been mentioned before, she was an albino: her hair, eyebrows, and body hair were all white. In the north such a person is called a \"Heaven's Elder\"; in the south, a \"white lamb.\" On top of this, her temper was fierce and imperious. She was already thirty years old, famed throughout the surrounding area, and no one had been willing to take her — so she had been given to Yuanmao for want of a better match. Yuanmao had had no idea. He came back into the room in high spirits, thinking to himself: \"Just now Pingcai's joke was aimed at my nearsightedness, and she went and cursed him for it, and threw something besides. We haven't even been properly intimate yet, and already she's defending me like that — whoever heard of a wife as devoted as this?\"",

    // P13
    "He hurried the maids and escort-women out, took off his outer robe, bolted the door, trimmed the candle to a good bright flame, lifted the curtain, drew aside the red veil, and held the lamp close. Yuanmao felt his bones go soft and his sinews melt with delight. There before him was a face like a silver basin, peach-blossom fair; a head of black hair like dark clouds; two curving, vivid black brows; a small cherry mouth, red as crimson; a fragrance of powder and oil, a breath of orchid and musk. Yuanmao was beyond himself with joy. He helped her out of her outer garments, and the new bride slipped first into the bedclothes. Yuanmao hastily undressed and slid in after her, and what followed between them was a matter that need not be described — suffice to say the bride yielded by degrees and the first union was duly accomplished.",

    // P14
    "The new bride handed him a handkerchief. Yuanmao remembered something about the practice of the \"original red\" and used it to wipe himself, then tucked it under the pillow to examine the next morning. He lay there thinking that this was truly a very satisfying experience, and tried to think of something to say, but nothing came to mind. He slept for a while, then rose again for a second union. The whole bed of quilts was newly padded cotton; moreover it was the tenth of the second month and the air had already turned warm. The exertion left Yuanmao steaming like a pot, sweat pouring down his head without stopping. He came to rest at last, and in the cooling-down happened to feel the handkerchief; forgetting he had already used it, he took it up and wiped his face and head with it. Then he pulled back half the quilt to let the heat escape and drifted off to sleep.",

    // P15
    "Very early in the morning the new bride rose first and went to comb her hair in another room. Yuanmao got up, washed his face, and dressed; then, quietly slipping the handkerchief into his pocket, he tried to go and watch his bride at her morning toilette — but was caught by an escort-woman who dragged him out to pay his respects to his father-in-law, and then there were various senior relations to greet, and the delay stretched on. By the time the bride had finished her dressing and sat in the room in her finest attire with her head bowed, Yuanmao sidled up and managed to squeeze out a few words; the bride could only smile without replying, but she stole a glance at him — a broad-featured face with good proportions, except for the eyes and brows nothing really remarkable, but far better-looking than her two brothers, and she felt not displeased. Then she looked again and noticed a dusky, mottled darkness on his face — patches and streaks of it, deep and light in different places, patchy and uneven, like a man who had rubbed coal-black onto his face and not wiped it off clean. She thought to herself: \"He must wash without soap. Tomorrow I'll tell him to scrub harder.\" Yuanmao stared at her with extreme satisfaction, thinking: \"Life is good now. No more wandering about outside.\" He also thought of the handkerchief and stepped into the outer room where no one could see, drew it from his breast, and held it stretched out between both hands for inspection. He stood stock-still. After a moment he thought: \"I must have taken the wrong one.\" He turned back inside, lifted every corner of the bedclothes — nothing; searched under the quilt and under the pillow — nothing either.",

    // P16
    "A maidservant nearby asked, \"Son-in-law, what are you looking for? Let me help.\" Yuanmao looked around and saw the room full of maids and old serving-women; there was no way he could say. He had to go out again to a place with no one about, and hold the handkerchief up for close examination. He saw a series of streaks that were not quite lacquer, not quite oil, not quite ink — he truly could not guess what it was. He sniffed it: a faint oily fragrance, with a trace of perspiration; he gave a sudden snort of laughter and thought, \"No wonder her younger brother is full of learned quotations — even inside his sister's — even there such dark fluid abounds.\" Then he reconsidered: \"That's impossible.\" He turned the handkerchief over and examined it again very closely, and at one spot, at the edge of the black oil, there seeped a faint reddish tinge, like diluted rouge-water, odorless. He thought it over carefully for quite some time, and was suddenly struck by enlightenment. \"That's it — that's it! This faint red shadow is undoubtedly the original red. As for all the black — someone must have been playing a prank yesterday and smeared some dark oil on my hat or onto my head, and with the sweating I wiped my head by mistake with this cloth.\" He tucked it back into his sleeve. He went in and ate the morning-after wedding feast, and in the warmth of new marriage the two were to each other as brother and sister.",

    // P17
    "After a few days, when Yuanmao was making the rounds of thanks to the matchmakers and paying calls on well-wishers, Wang Xun and Zhongqing asked him how he found his new wife. He said nothing about anything else, but kept talking about hair — one person said it was white silk-fine hair, another said it was silver thread and crane feathers — and no one could make out what he meant. People saw how delighted he was and were thoroughly puzzled.",

    // P18
    "Then Yuanmao recalled the incident when Pingcai had been cursed — the joke had touched on white hair and white intimate-hair, and that was what had made the bride so furious. His suspicions began to stir. And furthermore: every day his own face was becoming stained with a dark oiliness, and there was the strange matter of the handkerchief; and she rose very early and combed her hair in a separate room, always behind a closed door — what did all that signify? He could not resolve his doubts and dared not ask directly. One day he came into the room and saw her in high spirits, bedecked in pearls and jade, her hair plainly full and black, blacker than lacquer. He tried to get close enough to smell her head, but she pushed him away. He suddenly thought: perhaps her hair was naturally black while her intimate hair was white — and that was what people's remarks had been about. He thought again: even if she had a few white intimate hairs, how would outsiders know? But if that were truly the case, it wouldn't do. Then he thought: I must not entertain such ideas. Tonight I'll pull one out and look at it tomorrow — that will tell me all I need to know. He waited impatiently for dusk, and when they had gone to bed, he felt about for that precious thing — a lush, woolly patch of growth — but he could not bring himself to pull any, for fear of causing her pain. So he went ahead with his usual carrying-on, and afterward, feeling about with his hand in hopes that something might have naturally come loose and would put his mind at rest, he suddenly found that he did indeed have one. He was overjoyed; he pinched it tight between two fingers, reached out one hand to grope for a piece of paper under the mat, wrapped it up carefully, and then, having nowhere safe to put it, tucked it into the fold of his braid at the very top of his head for fear she might find it.",

    // P19
    "Madam Sun could not imagine what he had been doing. Yuanmao had spent half the night at his maneuvers, and in the morning slept in. Madam Sun had long since finished combing her hair. When Yuanmao finally got up and was washing his face, he remembered the paper packet in his braid, hurriedly put on his hat, ran into the outer room, opened it up — and found a single jet-black strand.",

    // P20
    "Yuanmao was delighted. \"I've been suspecting for nothing these several days — those sharp-tongued gossips were just talking nonsense.\" And his mind was at rest. What a fool that Yuanmao was — spending half the night on his scheme, obtaining a single hair, which all along was one of his own that had rubbed off onto his hand. He attributed it to his wife's and considered his suspicions entirely dissolved.",

    // P21
    "About half a month passed, and then one day the truth came out. While Madam Sun was combing her hair she felt a chill and called a maidservant to fetch her a sleeveless jacket from the other room. Yuanmao was already up, and seeing the maid carrying clothes into that other room, he followed along without enough time for the door to be closed. There, seated, was a figure dressed in a scarlet close-fitting garment, with a cascade of silver-silk hair — over three feet of it — hanging loose, and two eyebrows of a pale gold color. Li Yuanmao's heart gave a tremendous lurch; he thought he had encountered a ghost and almost turned and fled. But then he thought: the clothes are clearly hers — could she really be some white apparition? He hurried forward — and Madam Sun herself was so startled that before she could conceal anything her face had flushed scarlet. Li Yuanmao looked closely, and a rush of indignation rose straight to his head. \"So that's how it is!\" he cried. \"My luck has well and truly run out — I've married a goblin. This is the Ageless Crone from Journey to the West. She wants a husband too — laughable, utterly laughable!\" Madam Sun heard this, and in a torrent of shame and fury burst into tears and shouted: \"We've treated you so well — I am a young lady of a good family, and we've received you as a son-in-law, a man of no rank or prospects, and still you aren't satisfied, still you find fault! So what if my hair is a bit white — in every other respect, am I not your match? Or are you too fine for a mere cross-eyed man to aspire to? If you find fault with me, you can just divorce me!\" She flew into a rage, and pots and ornaments flew about crashing on the floor. Li Yuanmao retreated to the other room muttering and cursing, and the two of them kept it up the whole morning.",

    // P22
    "As it happened, Madam Sun had for some time been mixing sesame oil with lampblack and then adding persimmon lacquer. She would first comb her hair out neatly and then carefully paint on the mixture — the effect was sleeker and glossier than natural hair. The process required washing once a day; otherwise the hair became impossible to comb and the lacquer would not go on again. For washing she used a bucket of soapberry water with borax and alum to clean it thoroughly, then dried it to half-dampness before combing and setting, which took the better part of an hour. That morning she had been running a little late, and so the truth came to light. Yuanmao stormed out in a fury and went to stay at Wei Pingcai's lodgings for a couple of days. Pingcai asked him what had happened, and Yuanmao had no choice but to tell him the whole story. Pingcai was immediately enlightened: he now understood how his joke the other night had hit exactly on the mark.",

    // P23
    "Madam Sun, seeing her husband fail to return for two or three days, grew anxious and reported the matter to her parents. Lianggong was furious; Madam Lu too was displeased, and she sent someone to the Mei household to inquire — he was not there. After searching everywhere, he was found at Pingcai's. Yuanmao still refused to go back; only after Pingcai pressed him earnestly did he agree to return with the messenger, though he still would not go into the inner chambers and sat in the study chatting idly with Sihui instead. When Lianggong returned that evening he gave Yuanmao a talking-to, and Madam Lu reproved him as well — though at heart she felt they had somewhat wronged Yuanmao — and between scolding and coaxing persuaded him to go in. Yuanmao had no choice but to comply, but the memory of that apparition was still with him and he could not bring himself to be cheerful.",

    // P24
    "Madam Sun, seeing him come in, wanted him to speak first and apologize, and sat without stirring. In the lamplight Yuanmao looked again and saw her distinctly black and white — a real beauty — and his heart softened a little. He spoke first. Madam Sun slowly replied. Yuanmao sat with head bowed and eyes shut, pondering for a while, and then suddenly a brilliant idea struck him; he jumped up and grinned at her. Madam Sun, seeing him beginning to come around, made a show of playing hard to get — she regarded him coolly and said nothing, studying her own reflection in the mirror. Yuanmao could not help saying: \"Why not just tell me the truth — what's the point of hiding it from me? Now that we're married it's not as if we can undo it. I see you have to lacquer your hair every day, which is a great deal of trouble and very inconvenient, and every day it rubs off on my face and people laugh at me. I've thought of a solution that's simpler, more attractive, and won't leave oil on my face — would you care to hear it?\" Madam Sun, curious about what scheme he had devised, asked, \"And what would that be?\" Yuanmao said, \"Like a young female role in the opera — put on a hairnet and tie it up. Who would ever see through that silver hair underneath? Or better yet, just shave it off entirely — that would be cleanest of all.\" Madam Sun said, \"Shaving it off won't do. A hairnet, as you suggest — that would be convenient enough. And I am tired of all that lacquering. Tomorrow morning I'll send someone to buy one.\" Yuanmao said, \"You ought to scrape your face with a razor every day too — otherwise a few pale fine hairs will come out. If you shave your down and wear the hairnet, you could easily pass for a great beauty.\"",

    // P25
    "Madam Sun was pleased by this, and her expression softened into smiles. She said, \"It's still early — why not send someone to buy it now, so it's ready for tomorrow morning?\" Yuanmao said, \"Buy it now and we can use it tonight — it'll save smearing my face again.\" Madam Sun called a maidservant to go tell the steward to buy one hairnet, one hairpiece, and one swallow-tail ornament, and to bring them back promptly. In short order everything was purchased. Madam Sun was overjoyed, and at once she put a pot of soapberry water on to boil, then scrubbed the lacquered oil from her hair — the washwater ran dark as the blue vats in a dyer's shop. Not even waiting for it to dry, she let Yuanmao blot it with a cloth, blotting and then blotting again.",

    // P26
    "Yuanmao then suggested she trim and shave back the temple-hair and the hairline all around so nothing would show. Madam Sun had an old serving-woman take a razor and shave all around the edges, and shaved off the eyebrows entirely as well; the fine down on her face was shaved smooth too. Then the hairnet was fitted on, the real hair coiled once around the base, the false hairpiece pinned in place with a clasp, the swallow-tail ornament tied in, a jade kingfisher ornament set on the forehead, and eyebrows painted on — and she truly became several degrees more handsome.",

    // P27
    "By evening she looked for all the world like the Tipsy Lady Yang. Madam Sun had two large candles lit and used two mirrors, one in front and one behind, to admire herself from all angles — she found the effect breathtaking. Yuanmao, looking at her, felt his heart blossom with delight; he stepped close, smelled the top of her head, rubbed his cheek against her face — only the faintest trace of oil, nothing like before. In high good spirits he dismissed the maids, took her by the hand to bed, and under the quilt together they bloomed like the night-opening flower. Then Yuanmao suddenly recalled the hair-pulling episode of the other night and asked Madam Sun, \"I've heard that those with albinism have white hair all over their bodies — so why is your intimate hair dark?\" Madam Sun said, \"It isn't exactly dark.\" Yuanmao said, \"Dearest, let me have a look.\"",

    // P28
    "Madam Sun refused. Yuanmao said, \"Can you still be keeping things from me? After all I've done to fix things for you — what is there to hide?\" Madam Sun said nothing. Yuanmao climbed naked out of bed, took up the candle, folded back the quilt. Madam Sun tried to shield herself, but Yuanmao could already see that her body was truly white as frost and snow, which he found quite charming.",

    // P29
    "When he came to that most intimate area, it was as if he had ridden upon a silver-maned horse — and indeed it bore out Pingcai's joke, looking for all the world like a fly-whisk held over herself. Yuanmao could not suppress a laugh, and gave her a pinch. Madam Sun said, \"What do you think you're doing — aren't you yourself a nearsighted man? Why not have a good sniff as well?\" Yuanmao, moved by what he had seen, set down the candle and climbed back into bed. What followed between them need not be told. As to what happened next, listen to the following chapter for the explanation.",
  ],

  40: [
    // P0
    "To return to our story: after the last encounter in which Xi Shiyi had been humiliated by Qinyan and went home in a fury, he had been racking his mind for some way to take revenge but could think of nothing, and so contented himself with spreading gossip wherever he went — saying that Qinyan had been performing at parties outside, that Qinyan had treated him very warmly and actually wanted to follow him home.",

    // P1
    "He concocted a good deal of slander and so vented a portion of his rage. As for the bracelet, when Juhua asked about it, Xi Shiyi simply claimed he had dropped it carelessly and it had shattered; Juhua could do nothing about it. But Baying happened to tell her the truth, and Juhua made a tremendous scene. Xi Shiyi pleaded softly and promised to replace it with a finer one when he found one, and so the matter was settled. Xi Shiyi's character was truly laughable — he was forever abandoning the old for the new. Previously he had bought Chunlan and treated her very well, but grew tired of her in under half a year. Last year he had acquired Baying, whom he treasured like a gem, and now he had got himself entangled with Deyue and Zhuo Tianxiang, so that he had already grown cold toward Baying.",

    // P2
    "Baying, full of resentment, fell to chatting idly with Chunlan one day and said, \"Chunlan, the old country bumpkin used to treat us both so well — and now it's one forgotten for the next. Can you really take that calmly?\" Chunlan said, \"I was foolish in the past. When he took me out of apprenticeship I really thought he was a loyal and feeling man — little did I know he has no conscience at all. Look at what he gets up to: nothing but harm and injury to people. That barrel of his — I don't know how many men he lured with it. They say some of them were from respectable families, and when they got home some hanged themselves or drowned themselves. What sort of retribution is coming to him, I wonder?\" Baying said, \"I've heard about the barrel — what was so special about it that it could trap men?\"",

    // P3
    "Chunlan said, \"The barrel was made in Western fashion — a narrow top and a wide bottom, with something inside that clinked and chimed like bells. He would throw something in and make the person reach in and get it out. There was a partition in the middle with two holes — each hole only wide enough for one hand. If a person put both hands in, he would trip the mechanism inside, locking both hands so they couldn't be withdrawn. The person was then at his mercy, bent over and helpless, to do with as he pleased. I was taken in by it the very first time. Later someone reported it and the barrel was finally smashed to pieces.\"",

    // P4
    "Baying said, \"It would at least be tolerable if he showed some constancy to people. He used to shower gifts, but now even gifts are rare — it's as if we owe him our backsides in tribute. A man like that — it's a wonder he doesn't get sores. If it all rotted off, we'd all be rid of the trouble.\" Chunlan said, \"You still have your old master here. If he grows too cold to you, you can ask leave and go back to serving Master Ji — I think that would be better than staying with him.\" Baying said, \"That Master Ji is even worse — if he were good, I wouldn't have changed situations. That man makes your skin crawl, and on top of everything he's stingy — he'd wear a person out all day and then give only a few dozen cash, with a couple of small coins added in, so I wanted nothing more to do with him. When I was working at my trade back home, how free and easy life was — even braiding a queue earned several hundred cash. Come evening after supper, a few close friends would go out together — to the teahouse, the wine-shop, joking and laughing, as merry as could be. Wontons, steamed buns, three-treasure noodles in big bowls — whatever you fancied. And at the gambling table, if someone won, they'd toss out eight hundred cash or more without blinking — generous and flush. From the day I followed that man surnamed Ji, my luck went downhill.\" Chunlan said, \"That Master Ji's appearance really doesn't appeal to people either — when he talks to you he shows two yellow teeth between his lips, which is most unpleasant.\" Baying said, \"And his body has that foxy, musky stench.\"",

    // P5
    "But let us leave idle talk aside. To return to our story: one day Xi Shiyi came alone to the Hongji Temple. Both the monk and Pingcai had gone out; the young novice was in his own room, lying sideways on the kang facing the wall, asleep. Xi Shiyi found him in a close-fitting moon-white silk inner jacket trimmed with fancy borders, green crinkle-silk leg-warmers, and a freshly shaved gleaming bare head. Xi Shiyi felt desire stir at the sight. He removed his outer robe, lay down beside him, quietly untied his sash, and pulled his trousers halfway down, pressing close against him in intimate service. Deyue woke with a start, turned his head, saw Xi Shiyi, and said, \"You can't do this.\" Xi Shiyi paid no heed. Deyue said again, \"I really mean it — you can't do this.\" Xi Shiyi still thought he was playing coy and pressed forward another step — when suddenly from deep within Deyue's belly came a loud rumbling gurgle. Deyue cried out \"Oh no!\" his body jerked, and a blast of hot air rushed out. Xi Shiyi felt it below as if immersed in hot water, then withdrew abruptly; with a great explosive sound, a torrent of liquid stool shot out, splattering all over Xi Shiyi's abdomen. Xi Shiyi cried, \"What is this!\" and rolled off the kang in haste.",

    // P6
    "Deyue scrambled down after him, squatted immediately on the floor, and with a great rushing sound released a large puddle — the stench was overpowering. Xi Shiyi held his nose and peered at the floor; there seemed to be something resembling pus and blood among it.",

    // P7
    "Xi Shiyi found some paper and began wiping himself; the crotch of his trousers and even the sash ties had caught a good deal, and he wiped everything clean one by one. Deyue wrinkled his brow, shifted himself aside, and only then finished and got up. They could not call anyone in to clean it up, so Deyue himself scooped some ash from the coal brazier to cover it and swept it clean. Xi Shiyi said, \"What am I supposed to do — hurry and bring a basin of water for me to wash up.\" Deyue said, \"I told you, you couldn't do this, and you wouldn't listen.\" He found a small earthen basin, ladled in some water, and handed Xi Shiyi a foot-cloth; Xi Shiyi made do and wiped himself off.",

    // P8
    "Deyue lay back down. Xi Shiyi was thoroughly disgusted. Deyue said, \"I'm unwell and my stomach is unsettled; I'm not in the mood to talk. You'd better go.\" Xi Shiyi had no choice but to leave — and just then ran straight into Zhuo Tianxiang coming in, colliding squarely with him. Xi Shiyi said, \"The monk and Master Wei are both out; Deyue is sick and not up to company — don't bother going in.\" Tianxiang said, \"Let's go sit in Master Wei's quarters then — even though he's not home, we can still sit there.\" Xi Shiyi had no particular objection and went with Tianxiang inside, where he had Pingcai's servant brew two bowls of tea, and fell to chatting idly with Tianxiang. Tianxiang said, \"Today I came to find Master Wei because I need to borrow a few strings of cash from him, and of course he's not home — I don't know when he'll be back.\" Xi Shiyi said, \"Where have you come from just now? You're covered in dust.\" Tianxiang said, \"I went to collect money from that Muslim butcher who sells beef, and I didn't find him either.\" Xi Shiyi said, \"How much money do you need?\" Tianxiang said, \"I'm still fifteen strings short and simply can't scrape it together.\" Xi Shiyi said, \"What's so urgent?\" Tianxiang said, \"Yesterday Cuiguan was swindled out of eighty strings by some people and signed a note for it; they're coming to collect today, and we said we'd have it by tomorrow.\" Xi Shiyi said, \"Who swindled Cuiguan?\" Tianxiang said, \"Who else but the grassy-radical crowd? Yesterday they had him come and serve for a whole day, then trussed him up and accused him of stealing a snuff bottle, threatening to take him to the north yamen. The boys who went with him begged and pleaded until finally those people's attendants played the go-between and worked out a settlement of eighty strings, with a note signed — and only then was he let go.",

    // P9
    "\"Today we've pawned all our clothes and only got sixty strings, borrowed another five, and the Muslim fellow still owes us a few strings but we can't find him. So now I'm begging the honored gentleman to give fifteen strings to settle the matter.\" Xi Shiyi said, \"What's the worry — it's not due until tomorrow. Let's sit here a while, then go to Pan Sanyе's shop and write a draft on his account.\" Tianxiang thanked him, and the two sat together chatting.",

    // P10
    "As it happened, Tianxiang had gone to find the Muslim butcher; the butcher was out, but his nephew, who had some attachment to Tianxiang, found him at home and kept him in the shop to eat two small bowls of beef and five or six steamed buns, after which they did some business of no great consequence, and Tianxiang was given two strings of cash. What Tianxiang did not know was that the young Muslim had just contracted syphilis, which had not yet broken out — and in this encounter he had passed it on to Tianxiang. Tianxiang at this moment was feeling a burning, scalding discomfort at his rear passage and was hoping Xi Shiyi might help put out the fire. Xi Shiyi, seeing Tianxiang in an aroused mood, was himself willing enough; and so without a word said between them they went at it for a while, Pingcai still having not returned.",

    // P11
    "Xi Shiyi had been about to go with Tianxiang to collect the draft from Pan San's, but suddenly felt a rush of fire in his body, his temples throbbing and swelling with pain, a general sense of illness coming on — so he dashed off a quick note and sent Tianxiang to collect by himself. Xi Shiyi went straight home; he was dizzy and faint and could barely hold himself together.",

    // P12
    "He undressed and spent the night in a fever as if burning from within, and his lower parts ached abominably. He reached down with his hand — wet and dripping all down one thigh, the organ hot to the touch, already swollen to the size of a wine cup.",

    // P13
    "He groaned without ceasing through the night. Juhua could not sleep at all, and in the morning when she saw the state of that organ she was horrified; she asked hurriedly what had happened, but Xi Shiyi would not come straight out and say, claiming only that he had no idea why it had suddenly swollen up. Juhua said, \"Let us send for a doctor to have a look.\" Xi Shiyi said, \"Master Tang the monk is very good — he specializes in exactly these conditions.\" Juhua sent someone to summon him.",

    // P14
    "Now, the monk Tang had for some days observed that Deyue's complexion was sickly and his fingernails were turning blue, and knew he had absorbed some toxic substance. He had administered a purging decoction to drive out the poison and reduce the fever, and yesterday Deyue had purged several times — as Xi Shiyi had conveniently discovered, the poison entering him directly through the kidney channel and proceeding straight to the heart channel. Xi Shiyi's constitution was already depleted, and then he had gone on to engage with Tianxiang, who had freshly contracted the syphilitic poison from the young Muslim — which Xi Shiyi had also absorbed into himself. Two poisons simultaneously erupting made the condition extremely severe. Shortly the monk arrived, asked how he had fallen ill, and Xi Shiyi gave an account that included only his encounter with Tianxiang. The monk took his pulse and prescribed another purging decoction. But the poison had struck too deep, and the purging was not enough to bring it out; after three days the condition only worsened. The swollen and ulcerating area had broken open; Xi Shiyi was in unbearable torment and had to engage yet another physician, who demanded two hundred taels of gold to guarantee a cure. Treatment proceeded both internally and externally — but this new doctor was not even as skilled as the monk, nor did he have any superior medicines; the ulceration spread wider and wider, and what had once resembled a small monk's bald head now resembled a wasp's nest, the stench indescribable. Xi Shiyi found he could not sleep lying down and had no choice but to sit all day without his trousers, wearing only his leg-warmers on a stool, both feet spread wide open, with two small footstools propping them up, while the rotting, eggplant-like thing dangled between them — his heart a pit of misery and desperation.",

    // P15
    "Juhua, looking on, was heartbroken but dared not reproach him; she could only pray to the gods and make vows, nursing him with every care. Two or three physicians came and went, and the afflicted organ was reduced to a candle-stub's worth. At last it was the monk Tang who, having learned of this, applied the finest quality Zhibao Dan salve, and so preserved that Pillar of Posterity — all of one inch and more remaining. After the wound finally healed, it was a limbless stump, flesh withered and skin slack, resembling nothing anyone could name. As for marital relations — that was plainly out of the question henceforth. Such was Xi Shiyi's retribution for his debaucheries.",

    // P16
    "And now for a tale of curious coincidence — truly laughable when one hears it. In Pan San's shop there was a young assistant named Xu Laosan, only sixteen years old, and quite a comely lad. Pan San had long coveted him and had tried to trick him on several occasions, but had never managed to get his hands on him. The boy had one weakness: he liked a drink, and when he had drunk too much he would fall asleep. On the fifteenth of the first month, all the other shop assistants went home for the festival; Pan San kept only Laosan behind and sat drinking wine with him in the small back office. Xu Laosan was already drunk and lay asleep on the kang.",

    // P17
    "Pan San had long since prepared his vile scheme. He had gone to the barber's and collected some short-clipped hair trimmings and shavings, which he concealed on his person. Taking advantage of the boy's drunkenness, he violated him by force, and then stuffed the hair cuttings inside him, intending that the irritation would bring the boy crawling back for relief. When Xu Laosan awoke and found what had been done to him, he wanted to cry out, but shame held him back, and he had to bear it in silent humiliation.",

    // P18
    "From that day on he developed a persistent complaint. Knowing perfectly well that he had been deceived by Pan San and had something implanted in him, he was filled with hatred — yet he suppressed it, said nothing, and ignored Pan San entirely. Pan San, congratulating himself on the success of his scheme, was confident the boat would drift toward the bank on its own. Little did he know that Xu Laosan nursed his grievance in his heart. He had a brother-in-law, Zhou Xiaosan, who happened to drive Pan San's cart — a man of considerable spirit, the sort who would draw a sword to aid a stranger in distress.",

    // P19
    "After the outrage, Xu Laosan immediately told his brother-in-law. Zhou Xiaosan was at once ready to go and make a scene with Pan San, but Laosan held him back, and together they devised a clever scheme for revenge.",

    // P20
    "The next day Laosan went home. He had no parents, only two elder brothers: one ran a small wine-shop that sold smoked meats and sausages; the other was an idle layabout who did comic performances in an acrobat's troupe — a tumbler named Xu Er. His sister also lived at home. He described the outrage he had suffered; the hatred was bone-deep, and he swore vengeance. His second brother, hearing the story, immediately stripped off his jacket and made as if to run out and start a fight.",

    // P21
    "His elder brother pulled him back and said, \"This is not a matter for fighting — let's think it over. Go and invite Uncle Li San; he's the one who recommended Laosan for that job. We'll go reason with him and see what he has to say.\" The sister said, \"Fighting won't do, and going to reason with him won't do either. There's no physical injury to show, so what are we going to do — report to the Board of Punishments for an examination of the body? As I see it, let me think of a scheme to make him suffer too — make him take a silent loss he can't even complain about.\"",

    // P22
    "The elder and second brothers said, \"Our sister makes a good point — but he's a man of forty or fifty; how do you propose to make him take such a silent loss?\" The sister laughed. \"Let me think it over carefully.\" This third sister was barely nineteen, exceptionally handsome, quick-witted and silver-tongued. Had she been born a man she would have been capable of great things; as fate would have it she was born a woman. She thought for a while, then laughed. \"I have a perfect scheme — only it lacks one particular person.\" The second brother said, \"If it's to avenge my little brother, I'll go into water or into fire without a second thought.\" The sister said, \"This job has no use for you, and besides, I can't explain it to you — if I did, you'd blab.\"",

    // P23
    "The second brother flared up: \"What kind of talk is that? If we're out to deceive someone, do you think I'd go around telling people?\" The sister said, \"It only requires this and that, so and so, and that's all there is to it.\" The elder brother thought to himself: \"Your sister-in-law is not much to look at and wouldn't attract anyone's eye — and anyway she's gone back to her parents' home. Should we bring in Old Ba's wife? Or invite the Ge girl?\" The sister said, \"That won't work. Those women of that trade are neither kith nor kin — they may not be willing to come. And besides, Pan San knows those women.\"",

    // P24
    "The second brother laughed. \"Sister, we're all flesh-and-blood family. Since we're avenging our brother, we should all do our share. On that day, what's the harm in using you as the lure? It's not as if anything would actually happen to you. As long as we keep a sharp eye and come rushing in quickly, that's all — and we'll certainly want your husband there too. If we shake him down for money, it stays in the family — isn't that better than paying someone outside?\"",

    // P25
    "The sister spat at him. \"You talk rubbish! Why don't you wait for your own second sister-in-law to come serve as the lure?\" The second brother laughed. \"She's not even married in yet — who has patience to wait a year and a half? If she were already in the house, why would I be asking you? I'd put her to use directly.\"",

    // P26
    "The elder brother, seeing that the plan would bring both revenge and money, joined in urging her: \"What Old Er says makes sense — there really is no one but you who can do this. But once it's done, there's Laosan on one side, and as for your husband, that pot is going to be smashed as well.\" The sister said, \"That hardly matters — three strings of cash a month, you can find that elsewhere. Since we've settled on the plan, we'd better move quickly. Go fetch my husband. We all need to agree, and he needs to be willing.\" Zhou Xiaosan was summoned; the sister explained what had been arranged, and Zhou Xiaosan agreed to everything. They fixed on the evening of the day after next for the operation.",

    // P27
    "One day passed; the next morning, the second brother went to Pan San's to collect Laosan's belongings. Pan San, sensing that the matter had come to light, was somewhat frightened and tried to detain the boy. Zhou Xiaosan pressed hard, the bedroll stayed, and the second brother was talked into going home. Pan San was deeply grateful to Xiaosan and offered his thanks; Xiaosan said, \"Three Master, if you truly mean to look after my brother-in-law, I'll go persuade him to come back tomorrow. This boy is thick-headed, but with a few words of guidance from me he'll come to his senses. And by lucky chance there's something convenient that may suit you for tomorrow — I don't know whether Three Master would care to honor us?\" Pan San said, \"What do you mean! Even though you drive my cart, you're as good as a partner. Since you understand loyalty, is there anything I wouldn't agree to?\" Xiaosan said, \"If Three Master is pleased to honor us, then we can certainly arrange it.\" He added, \"Tomorrow happens to be my wife's birthday, and there won't be a single relative at our house. Elder Brother and Second Brother both have business and can't come; only Laosan will be there. Tomorrow evening I'd like to invite Three Master to come sit at our place, and with Laosan right there I can speak plainly and tell him to come back — that'll settle everything.\" Pan San was delighted. \"Excellent — if you handle this completely, I'll see you promoted. I'll add a string of cash to your monthly wage.\" Xiaosan said, \"Many thanks to Three Master.\" When the appointed evening came, Xiaosan walked home with Pan San on foot. Pan San sat in the front room; Xiaosan went inside and brought out a cup of tea. Pan San said, \"Since today is your wife's birthday, I ought to offer congratulations. Please invite your wife to come out and exchange a bow.\" Xiaosan said, \"How could I dare ask for congratulations. I'll ask her to come out and kowtow in thanks for Three Master's many kindnesses.\"",

    // P28
    "He called twice: \"Third Sister! Third Sister!\" A response was heard from within — such a soft, tender voice, instantly pleasing to the ear. Pan San heard a light, high-heeled click-clicking approaching, then a hand appeared on the doorframe — two silver-tipped fingers appeared — and a voice said: \"What is it?\" Xiaosan said, \"Three Master has come for the first time; you should come out and offer your respects. Besides, Three Master is a person of mature years — like a parent to us — there's no need to be shy.\" Third Sister gave a little laugh and said, \"I have something on the stove, and I haven't washed my hands yet. Laosan is so greedy — even though he can't help me, if I dish up a portion he'll still eat half of it.\" She laughed again and went back inside. Pan San, having heard all this, felt himself already beginning to melt; he thought to himself: \"What a voice — I wonder what her face is like. If she resembles her brother, that would be something.\" Xiaosan pulled out the table and set three places. Laosan first brought out a wine pot, two wine cups, and two pairs of chopsticks, then set out four dishes: a dish of salt-cured pork, a dish of smoked fish, a dish of sausage, and a dish of braised gluten. Xiaosan poured the wine, and the two sat down. Pan San said, \"Laosan can come out and sit with us too.\" Xiaosan called Laosan out; Laosan said, \"I don't drink.\" Pan San said, \"Laosan, come, come, come — have a cup.\"",

    // P29
    "Laosan paid no attention and went back inside. Xiaosan said, \"He's helping his sister with the dishes — he'll come presently.\" Laosan then brought out two more dishes and two more bowls: a dish of sautéed pig liver, a dish of sautéed mutton, a bowl of braised vermicelli, and a bowl of fried mushroom caps.",

    // P30
    "The two had been drinking for a while when there came a banging at the door, and then two urgent shouts of \"Xiaosan! Xiaosan!\" Xiaosan hurried to open the door. Pan San heard a voice cry out \"This is terrible!\" — which gave him quite a start — and then a rush of words.",

    // P31
    "Xiaosan said, \"I'm coming.\" The person at the door said, \"Come quickly — don't delay.\"",

    // P32
    "Xiaosan came back inside and said to Pan San, \"Please sit a moment, Three Master. I'll ask Laosan to keep you company. Something's come up that I need to go settle; I'll be right back.\" Pan San said, \"I'll go too.\" Xiaosan said, \"No need to rush — I'll be back in a moment.\" Pan San's real reason for wanting to stay was Laosan; if Xiaosan left he would have a chance to make his advances. Though his mouth said he'd leave, his body didn't budge. Xiaosan called Laosan out, but Laosan flatly refused. Xiaosan cursed under his breath — \"Thick-headed boy!\" — and then called out: \"Third Sister, come out.\" Third Sister appeared in the doorway and said, \"What now?\" Xiaosan said, \"Your second brother has gotten himself into trouble and I need to go sort it out. Three Master is here, and Laosan won't come out. I thought — Three Master is a man of fifty or so; you could be his daughter. Just be easy about it and come out and keep him company while I go and return at once.\" Third Sister said, \"I wouldn't know how to keep someone company — I'm a woman, and if I made some blunder and offended Three Master, it would still be your fault, and Three Master would blame you.\" Pan San, hearing these few words, felt his soul dissolve; he desperately wanted her to come out, and so he jumped in: \"You're too kind, my lady — I had been meaning to offer my birthday wishes; please do come out!\" Pan San was already on his feet.",

    // P33
    "Third Sister came smiling out, and Pan San's spirit left his body entirely at the sight of her. She had a melon-seed face, a pair of phoenix eyes, her hair dressed in a large ingot-style coil with a flower pinned in it. She wore a mauve cotton blouse — the green-dyed cotton had been washed so many times it had taken on that color — and below, faintly visible, a pair of moon-white silk-padded trousers. Her bound feet were tiny — barely three inches — her figure neither too tall nor too short, neither too plump nor too slender. Her face bloomed with a fragrant smile as she bobbed a curtsy to Pan San. Pan San, desire already kindled, returned the bow hastily and invited her to sit. She would not sit, but turned to Xiaosan: \"Come back quickly, so Three Master doesn't have to wait and grow impatient.\" Xiaosan agreed, and could be heard outside saying, \"At the very fastest, I won't be back until the second watch — there's five or six li of road.\" With that he hurried away. Third Sister went out to latch the door, then came back and sat down. Pan San smiled all over his face and said, \"My lady — if I may ask your age?\" Third Sister said, \"Nineteen.\" Then she said, \"Three Master, our Xiaosan is a rough sort of man, and if his service has been lacking in any way, we are much in debt to Three Master's generosity and constant consideration. Poor folk have nothing to offer — just this little gesture. The wine isn't enough to make you drunk, the food isn't enough to fill you up.\" With that she swayed gracefully to the wine pot, filled a cup, and set it down before him.",

    // P34
    "Pan San was so overwhelmed with delight he could barely contain himself. He said, \"My lady, why not come and sit over here? It doesn't seem right to put you to so much trouble.\" Third Sister smiled and called out, \"Laosan — little Third Brother — come out here.\" Laosan said, \"I'm not coming. You keep him company.\" Third Sister laughed. \"You won't come and entertain your own guest, and expect me to do it for you — was there ever such a stubborn child? No wonder people take advantage of you.\" Pan San, sensing a meaning behind these words, said at once, \"Xiaosan is like family in my household — my lady, please just sit down, there's no impropriety in it.\" Third Sister said, \"I'm sitting here just the same.\" Pan San said, \"Though you're sitting, my lady, you're still rather far — it's harder to talk. Come and sit closer.\" Third Sister rose slightly, smiled faintly, and sat back down again. Pan San stood up, filled a cup of wine, and carried it over to Third Sister. \"Allow me to offer you a cup, my lady.\" Third Sister said, \"You are too kind, Three Master — please drink it yourself.\" But even as she said so she took it, adding, \"How can I let Three Master serve me?\" and drained it in one swallow. Then she walked to the table, wiped the cup with her hand, filled it again, and said, \"Three Master, please drink this cup.\" Pan San's heart was already drunk; he said breathlessly, \"How can I dare decline my lady's generous offer!\" He took the cup, and as he did, he squeezed her wrist with his other hand. Third Sister lowered her head. Pan San drank, then could no longer restrain himself; he draped his arm across Third Sister's fragrant shoulder and said, \"My lady, please sit — don't tire those little feet of yours.\" Third Sister only smiled, and did not move toward him. Pan San said, \"Xiaosan is never at home — isn't my lady lonely, with no one for company?\" Third Sister said, \"There used to be an old serving-woman, but she left a few days ago and we haven't hired a replacement yet.\" Pan San said, \"To have my lady's own hands prepare everything today — I am more than blessed.\" And he filled yet another cup and handed it over.",

    // P35
    "The wine ran out. Third Sister said, \"There's wine to be had — Brother, go and buy half a jin of the good baijiu from the main street. This wine was too weak. Go to the big shop on the street — don't you dare be lazy about the walk and buy from some corner stall.\" Laosan agreed, did not light a lamp, and went off by moonlight. Third Sister said, \"I'll bolt the door — he has to walk to the main street; it'll be a while.\" Pan San, seeing her go to latch the door, thought to himself: \"Now is the time. That woman has been giving me every signal — I must not let her down.\" Third Sister came back and sat down. Pan San at this moment was consumed by fire; his face flushed red. He crossed over to her. \"My lady, another cup.\" He sat down at the edge of her stool. Third Sister made as if to move away; Pan San immediately caught hold of her sleeve. Third Sister kept her head down and only laughed. Pan San's mind was in a spin; he took a deep breath, set down the cup, and with both arms clasped her around the waist. Third Sister said, \"Three Master, what are you doing, holding me like this?\" She glanced up at him sidelong. Pan San cried hastily, \"My dear — your son doesn't know what he's doing!\" He lifted Third Sister onto his lap, intending to kiss her.",

    // P36
    "Third Sister pushed him away with one hand. \"You mustn't — Three Master, you're really most improper, molesting a respectable married woman. If I were to call out, you'd be disgraced.\" Pan San said, \"My dear, have mercy on me!\" Third Sister said, \"You really fancy me? That's too easy — things aren't that simple! You've quite underestimated me.\" Pan San said, \"My lady, if you are willing to show me this kindness, whatever you say goes.\" Third Sister held back his face with one hand and clasped his hand with the other, feeling for his gold bracelet. Pan San understood; he thought to himself: she wants this — what can I do? He took it off and said, \"My lady, if you will do me this kindness and take pity on me, I give you this bracelet. In future I'll show you great generosity and raise Xiaosan's wages as well.\" Third Sister accepted the bracelet and slid it onto her own wrist, then laughed. \"Thank you kindly. Since I'm going to oblige you, don't go telling people.\" Pan San agreed again and again. He tried to pull at her trousers; Third Sister quickly jumped down. \"Come to the bedroom!\" she said, and walked ahead. Pan San followed close behind. When they reached the kang, Third Sister said, \"Take off your long robe and we can have a little play right here on the edge of the kang.\"",

    // P37
    "Third Sister sat to one side first. Pan San undid his robe, was in the midst of pulling down his trousers, and was just about to press forward — when suddenly he heard footsteps behind him. He spun around — got a terrible fright — and hurriedly tucked his trousers back in. Zhou Xiaosan had already come to the front; he gave a great shout, seized him by the collar, and bellowed, \"You enormous shameless beast — you turn out to be no kind of human being at all!\" Pan San went speechless with terror. Third Sister said quickly, \"Three Master wanted the chamber pot earlier — what did you think?\" Xiaosan cried, \"You shameless slut — you throw yourself at any man in sight, and still you try to explain it away in front of me! Is the chamber pot on your person?\" Third Sister screamed, \"Don't you dare make wild accusations against innocent people.\" Xiaosan said, \"He's been at you, and now you say I'm the one making accusations. There's nothing to argue about — we'll take it to the neighbors and let the community judge. I invite you in good faith to have a drink and you repay me by going after my wife!\" He began dragging Pan San toward the door. Pan San was frantic. \"Xiaosan, don't do this — we can talk it over properly. I am entirely in the wrong — I should never have entered your inner chambers. But we've been friends for so many years; take that into account and be a little lenient — there's nothing we can't sort out between us.\" Xiaosan said, \"What is there to sort out? This wife of mine I don't want anymore. I'll take both of you to the authorities and let the magistrate decide — whether he assigns her to you or to me, we don't need to argue here.\" Third Sister stood by, playing the weeping wife. Pan San was helpless and could only beg. Third Sister cried, \"You've gone mad! What have I done that you want to send me to divorce? If you take me to the authorities, I'll have my own things to say.\" She threw a glance at Pan San. Pan San said, \"Xiaosan, let go. We can talk — there's nothing I can't discuss.\" Xiaosan said, \"What is there to discuss? I don't want this woman anymore — bring me a thousand taels of silver and I'll let you off.\" Pan San said, \"A thousand taels — all right, we can discuss it, but let go first.\" Xiaosan said, \"Let go? Just like that?\" and threw Pan San down on the floor.",

    // P38
    "Pan San said, \"My lady, put in a word for me.\" Xiaosan said, \"Think it over — if you're willing to agree to bring a thousand taels, just say so like a good boy. If you won't, I'll truss you up and send you to the magistrate.\" Pan San said, \"I'm willing! I'm willing! But how can it possibly come to a thousand taels? I have drafts on me worth three hundred strings — take those.\" Xiaosan said, \"What's three hundred strings worth?\" Third Sister said, \"You should search your conscience too. Three Master has been so good to you — even if today he made a mistake, you ought to consider the kindness of all those past years. If you knew how to repay a favor, would Three Master truly not know how to do right by us?\" Pan San said, \"My lady speaks the truth. I'm a man who understands loyalty above all. Xiaosan — let's stay on good terms. There's not a day when I can't look after you — why must it come to this today?\" Xiaosan said, \"Then let's be clear about it. Since the goods have been enjoyed, once or a hundred times it's all the same — my green hat is on and won't come off. First give me the three hundred strings; after that pay sixty strings every month. Do you agree or not?\" Pan San said, \"I agree! I agree!\" Xiaosan released his grip; Pan San scrambled up, handed over the cash drafts, and straightened his clothes. Third Sister said to Xiaosan, \"Light a lamp and see Three Master home — he's had a fright.\" Xiaosan laughed. \"Three Master, don't be alarmed — we were only playing a prank.\" Pan San's heart finally settled, though it was still pounding. He said, \"Fine prank — this kind should only happen once.\" Xiaosan said, \"From now on, it's entirely up to you, old sir — we won't be playing any more pranks.\" Pan San steadied himself. Xiaosan went to light a lamp; Third Sister caught Pan San's sleeve from behind and whispered the word \"tomorrow\" low. Pan San, having failed to complete his business, was cheered by this and nodded repeatedly. Xiaosan escorted Pan San out. When Pan San left for home in high spirits, the very next morning he sent Xiaosan off to the countryside on an errand.",

    // P39
    "After breakfast, Pan San came to Xiaosan's house, found the door unlatched, and pushed it open. There was Third Sister inside, playing with a little dog. Pan San coughed once; Third Sister's face blossomed immediately into smiles.",

    // P40
    "Pan San said, \"Yesterday I was nearly frightened to death.\" Third Sister said, \"He only wanted the money — did you think he really meant to take you in?\" Pan San said, \"Is there anyone else in the house?\" Third Sister said, \"Who would there be?\" Pan San said, \"I'll go bolt the door.\" Third Sister said, \"It's warm today — it'll be more comfortable with your clothes off.\" Then she said, \"Oh, I'm urgent — I need to go,\" and ran out to the back courtyard to relieve herself. She called back to Pan San, \"You undress first and get under the quilt.\" Pan San dared not disobey; he had just stripped to the skin when Third Sister came in smiling, holding up her trousers with both hands. Pan San, now entirely reassured, stripped completely and climbed onto the kang, pulling the quilt over himself. Third Sister came to the edge of the kang as well.",

    // P41
    "Pan San said, \"Come quickly!\" and reached out to pull her. Third Sister laughed and said, \"Bolt the bedroom door.\" She had just turned to do so when from outside came a shout: \"Caught you in the act!\" — and the thunder of footsteps. Pan San's soul left his body. Zhou Xiaosan led in his two brothers-in-law, all holding bright naked knives and a thick hemp rope; they fell upon Pan San, pinned him down, and dragged him off the kang. Xu Laosan threw three or four punches and cursed: \"You son-of-a-bitch, you ruined my brother, and now you want to ruin my sister as well!\" Pan San had no choice but to kneel on the floor kowtowing. Xiaosan said, \"I spared your miserable life yesterday, and today you come to die again.\" And they tied Pan San up. Pan San was stark naked and could only beg for mercy. Xu Er said, \"You know how to do things to people's backsides — well, old uncle is going to return the favor.\" Pan San was frantic and begged desperately for mercy. Third Sister stood by, shaking with laughter. Then Second Brother extended a middle finger — thick as a small yellow radish — dipped it in a jar of oil, and worked it into Pan San's backside. Pan San let out a continuous stream of cries. Xu Er unwrapped a paper packet and stuffed in the medicinal powder and hair clippings, two or three insertions' worth. Pan San groaned, his legs kicking wildly. Fortunately his sphincter was tough with age and did not bleed. Xu Er finished and released Pan San. Pan San could only tremble. Elder Brother Xu said, \"Pan San, do you know your crime? Our perfectly good brother was violated by you — Heaven itself cannot overlook such an act. And you planted things inside him and made him a sick man for life, unable to live properly. That is why today we return the courtesy and make you into a filthy scabhead too — would you say this is deserved or not?\"",

    // P42
    "Pan San bowed his head and could say nothing. He put on his trousers, shoes, and stockings, then said to Xiaosan: \"Since you did this to avenge someone, you shouldn't have taken my money.\" Xiaosan said, \"What money did we take from you?\" Pan San said, \"Not only the money — there was also a gold bracelet of eight taels' weight.\" Xiaosan said, \"Go home and take us to court then.\" Third Sister said, \"Pan San, if you want to go to court, say so quickly — I need time to rehearse my testimony, so I don't stumble when I'm before the magistrate.\" Pan San was one man alone — how could he fight the four of them? He had no choice but to swallow his humiliation. And now the back passage was burning and stinging abominably. He tried to put on his outer robe. Zhou Xiaosan stepped forward and snatched it away. \"You think you're going out wearing that?\" Third Sister said, \"Give it to him — cover up that dog face of his.\" Pan San put on his clothes and walked toward the door. He heard Third Sister calling out with a laugh: \"Pan San, come back sometime when you're free — I'll find something to scratch that itch for you.\" The three of them clapped their hands and howled with laughter. Pan San, burning with shame and fury, tucked his head down and scurried away.",

    // P43
    "The four siblings and brother-in-law laughed for a good while longer. Third Sister said, \"This Pan San has really been dealt with properly — it's thanks to Second Brother for being willing to do such a drastic thing.\" Second Brother said, \"I didn't even use my full strength — I was worried about pulling his intestines out.\" Third Sister said, \"I have an idea about those three hundred strings of cash — I don't know whether my two elder brothers will agree.\" Elder Brother and Second Brother said, \"This business is entirely thanks to Sister's merit — whatever you say, we'll agree to without question.\" Third Sister said, \"Give one hundred strings to your brother-in-law as working capital, so he needn't drive carts anymore. Second Brother, you take thirty strings; Elder Brother, you take thirty as well. The remaining hundred and forty strings will be set aside as seed money for Laosan — find a shop and put it to work earning interest. Since it all came to us on his account, he should naturally get the larger share.\"",

    // P44
    "Both brothers said \"Quite right.\" Xiaosan had that very morning exchanged the drafts for cash with Pan San's agreement — all arranged in advance — and now he brought it out and gave it to Third Sister to distribute. After settling the division, Third Sister said, \"But the most important thing is getting Laosan's ailment treated — he must be cured first.\"",

    // P45
    "Elder Brother Xu said, \"What remedy could there be?\" Third Sister said, \"I've heard that eating buckwheat noodles can expel swallowed pig hair or sheep hair from the stomach. Shape the buckwheat noodle dough into dumplings, fill them with sugar, but don't cook them all the way through — leave them slightly underdone — and have him eat them for a couple of days. Perhaps they'll draw it all out.\" The two brothers said, \"Nothing could be easier — we'll go make some for him to eat right now.\" They sat a while longer, and then the two brothers took their money and went their separate ways. As to what happened next, listen to the following chapter for the explanation.",
  ],
};
